Abstract

Video caching can significantly improve backhaul traffic congestion by locally storing the popular content that users frequently request. A privacy-preserving method is desirable to learn how usersâ€™ demands change over time. As such, this paper proposes a novel resource-aware hierarchical federated learning (RawHFL) solution to predict usersâ€™ future content requests under the realistic assumptions that content requests are sporadic and usersâ€™ datasets can only be updated based on the requested contentâ€™s information. Considering a partial client participation case, we first derive the upper bound of the global gradient norm that depends on the clientsâ€™ local training rounds and the successful reception of their accumulated gradients over the wireless links. Under delay, energy and radio resource constraints, we then optimize client selection and their local rounds and central processing unit (CPU) frequencies to minimize a weighted utility function that facilitates RawHFLâ€™s convergence in an energy-efficient way. Our simulation results show that the proposed solution significantly outperforms the considered baselines in terms of prediction accuracy and total energy expenditure.

Index Terms:
Federated learning, resource-aware hierarchical federated learning, resource optimization, video caching.

I Introduction

Video streaming is the dominant source of data traffic, and 333 out of 555 video views occur on wireless devices [1]. As such, content caching [2] can become an integral part of modern wireless networks since it can save the backhaul transmission bandwidth and reduce network congestion by ignoring repetitive extractions of the same few popular videos the users repeatedly request from the far-away cloud.

Two major design components of an efficient video caching platform are content placement and content delivery [3]. Knowing which content the users will request in the near future can crucially help the provider in the content placement phase. However, it is often challenging to predict content popularity as it changes rapidly. Besides, many users may have their individual preferences for specific types of content that are not necessarily globally popular. While machine learning (ML) may accurately predict content popularity or user-specific content demand, the need for immense number of data samples for training the ML model poses challenges in wireless video caching platforms.

A further challenge arises from requirements for privacy and/or protection of business secrets. The user equipment (UE) makes a content request using its serving base station (BS) to the content service provider (CSP) in wireless networks. On the one hand, the UE and the CSP do not reveal the exact content ID/information to the BS, the former because they want to protect their privacy, and the latter because CSP and the (wireless) internet service provider (ISP) operating the BS are often competitors. On the other hand, the spatial information of the UEs is only known to the ISPs, which does not want to convey it to the CSP. As such, privacy-preserving coordination among the UEs, ISPs and CSP is required. Therefore, distributed and privacy-preserving federated learning (FL) [4] is ideal for video caching in wireless networks.

Some existing literature [5, 6, 7, 8, 9] acknowledged the need for privacy protection and proposed FL-based solutions for content caching. In [5], Qiao et al. proposed a FL solution for content caching in resource-constrained wireless networks using two separate deep reinforcement learning (DRL) agents to find a subset of clients and their local training rounds. Wang et al. also leveraged a similar strategy [6], where users and edge servers used two separate DRL agents to learn computation offloading and content placement strategies, respectively. Both [5] and [6] considered federated aggregation of the DRL agents. Jiang et al. used an offline individual content preference learning, followed by an adaptive context space partitioning and FL-based popularity prediction algorithm in [7]. Li et al. developed an attention-weighted FL algorithm for device-to-device wireless networks where they partition the UEs into groups based on mobility and social behaviors in [8]. Khanal et al. proposed a self-attention-based FL algorithm for content caching in vehicular networks where the moving self-driving cars, roadside units and macro BS work collaboratively to train the model in [9].

While the above studies recognized the privacy concern in content caching, the cooperation among the three entities, i.e., UE, BS and CSP, was not addressed. Besides, the above studies assumed that the clientâ€™s111We use the terms UE and client interchangeably throughout the paper. training dataset is readily available. In reality, a UEâ€™s content requests are sporadic, and its dataset only contains the requested contentâ€™s information. Moreover, since practical networks have hierarchical architectures where the client only communicates with its immediate upper tier, i.e., the BS [10], a hierarchical federated learning (HFL) solution is needed.

Motivated by the above facts, we propose a novel resource-aware hierarchical federated learning (RawHFL) algorithm for predicting clientsâ€™ future content requests. We consider that UEsâ€™ requests arrive based on their own requirements, and their datasets can only be updated with the requested contentâ€™s information. Incorporating the well-known system and data heterogeneity, we derive the convergence analysis that reveals that the global gradient norm depends on the successful reception of the clientsâ€™ trained accumulated gradients and their local training rounds. As such, we jointly optimize client selection and clientsâ€™ local training rounds and CPU cycles to minimize a weighted utility function that facilitates RawHFLâ€™s convergence and minimizes energy expense under delay, energy and radio resource constraints. Our extensive simulation results validate that the proposed solution outperforms existing baselines in terms of test accuracy and energy expense.

V-B Performance Analysis

We first observe the convergence performance of the proposed algorithm with respect to different |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}|â€™s in Fig. 3. Intuitively, when the selected client setâ€™s size is small, the global model is trained on fewer data samples. Under severe data heterogeneity, this may lead to poor performance if the clients are not selected appropriately. Besides, based on the objective function in (IV), the proposed solution proactively selects the clients that minimize the weighted utility function. Therefore, it is expected that RawHFL may take more global rounds to convergence when the |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}| is small. Our simulation results also show similar trends in Fig. 3. We observe that the test loss and test accuracy performances improve when |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}| increases. For example, with |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|=2superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’2|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}|=2, the test accuracy drops about 3%percent33\% when Kğ¾K is around 294294294, while the test accuracy reaches a plateau when Kğ¾K is about 175175175 with |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|=4superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’4|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}|=4.

However, while a larger |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}| may help RawHFL convergence faster, the bandwidth and energy costs also increase. More specifically, when |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}| increases, (28) must choose the defined number of clients so that the utility function is minimized. As such, it may select some clients with higher energy expenses. Our simulation results also validate this intuition. Fig. 3 shows the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the total energy expenses during each edge round eğ‘’e for different client set sizes. For example, the clients spend no more than 0.180.180.18 Joules of energy about 76%percent7676\%, 52%percent5252\%, 37%percent3737\% and 29%percent2929\% of the edge rounds, when |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|=2superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’2|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}|=2, |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|=4superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’4|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}|=4, |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|=6superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’6|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}|=6 and |ğ’°Â¯bk,e|=8superscriptsubscriptÂ¯ğ’°ğ‘ğ‘˜ğ‘’8|\bar{\mathcal{U}}_{b}^{k,e}|=8, respectively.

V-C Performance Comparisons

We next show performance comparisons with some baselines. To our best knowledge, no existing baseline exactly considers our system design and uses HFL for video caching. As such, we modify the traditional hierarchical federated averaging (H-FedAvg) algorithm [14] for comparison. In the modification, termed H-FedAvg-M111, we find the smallest number of local rounds that all clients can train their local models without violating their constraints. In the second modification, termed H-FedAvg-M222, we drop the straggler who cannot even perform a single local round and find the least number of local iterations that the rest of the remaining clients can perform without violating their constraints. In the third modification, termed H-FedAvg-UB, we consider the upper bound of H-FedAvg [14], where each client can perform LL\mathrm{L} local rounds without constraints. We assume Z=|ğ’°b|ğ‘subscriptğ’°ğ‘Z=|\mathcal{U}_{b}| for these baselines. Finally, we consider a naive popularity-based Top-Popular baseline.

In Fig. 3, we show the Top-M accuracy comparison of our proposed solution with these baselines. While a higher value of M should increase the accuracy, the baselines in constrained cases are expected to perform worse. Since all clients perform the same number of local rounds in H-FedAvg-M111, some ES may fail to train the model in some edge rounds as some clients may not have sufficient battery powers to offload their trained models due to poor channel conditions. H-FedAvg-M222 should work better than H-FedAvg-M111 as we drop these stragglers in H-FedAvg-M222. Besides, H-FedAvg-UB is the ideal case upper bound. Furthermore, since the clients request content following a popularity-preference tradeoff, the Top-Popular baseline is expected to perform worse. Our simulation results in Fig. 3, where the horizontal and the vertical lines show the mean and standard deviation of the test accuracies across all 484848 clients, also validate these trends. Particularly, our solution yields about 41.5%percent41.541.5\%, 31.7%percent31.731.7\% and 43.5%percent43.543.5\% higher (Top-111) test accuracies than H-FedAvg-M111, H-FedAvg-M222 and Top-Popular baselines, respectively. While RawHFL achieves nearly identical test accuracies compared to the H-FedAvg-UB baseline, our solution is energy efficient. We list the energy expenses of these baselines in Table II, which clearly indicates that our proposed solution outperforms these baselines.

VI Conclusion

We proposed a privacy-preserving RawHFL solution for video caching under a realistic content request model and real-time data sensing mechanism. Based on our convergence analysis and content request model, we optimized client selections, local training rounds and CPU frequencies jointly to minimize a weighted utility function that facilitated faster convergence energy-efficiently. Moreover, our results suggest a tradeoff between the number of participating clients that facilitates faster convergence and the corresponding resource expenses.
